            =0A=09=09=09=09=09=09<p class=3D"p_no_top">OK, I finally feel l=
ike doing this.</p><p>I=E2=80=99ll keep the normal categories, but there ar=
e two other new things that feel important. The first is that I fell into m=
aybe the most intense internet rabbit hole of my life, where I went from id=
ly typing "galant music" into Google Scholar to a full-blown attempt to lea=
rn piano out of an 1801 rulebook in the space of a week. I'm still going on=
 the rulebook, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partimento" tar=
get=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" class=3D"underlink bluelink" tabindex=3D"-1=
">partimento</a> practice in general, and it's completely transformed how I=
 understand classical music. It's sort of transformed my piano playing too,=
 though I do feel like I should be better by now given the amount of work I=
've put in. I think it just takes ages to build fluency unfortunately.</p><=
p>I already wrote about this new obsession in <a href=3D"https://bucketover=
flow.substack.com/p/june-2024-improvise-like-its-1799" target=3D"_blank" re=
l=3D"noopener" class=3D"underlink bluelink" tabindex=3D"-1">Improvising lik=
e it's 1799</a> and <a href=3D"https://lucykeer.com/notebucket/minimum-viab=
le-music/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" class=3D"underlink bluelink" =
tabindex=3D"-1">Minimal viable music</a>.</p><p>The other new thing is that=
 I started Alexander Technique lessons with Peter Nobes, who runs the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.alexandercentre.co.uk/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener=
" class=3D"underlink bluelink" tabindex=3D"-1">South Bank Alexander Techniq=
ue Centre</a> (where <a href=3D"https://expandingawareness.org/" target=3D"=
_blank" rel=3D"noopener" class=3D"underlink bluelink" tabindex=3D"-1">Micha=
el Ashcroft</a> trained). Unlike partimento practice, where I=E2=80=99ve bo=
red on at length about it to anyone who=E2=80=99ll tolerate listening, I=
=E2=80=99ve been pretty quiet about the Alexander Technique, particularly i=
n writing. That=E2=80=99s because it=E2=80=99s weird and subtle and I have =
no idea what's going on most of the time, so it's hard to talk about. It's =
really working though.</p><p>The effect of both of these is that after a co=
uple of rather stuck years I feel like I=E2=80=99m back in an open world wi=
th interesting new things in it. I don=E2=80=99t know where I=E2=80=99m goi=
ng but at least I=E2=80=99m going somewhere.</p><h2>Notebook</h2><p>Nothing=
 major happened here, but I still like it and write the odd post there. I a=
lso still read it back a lot =E2=80=93 something about the design seems to =
really work for that. I think it's mainly the high density list of posts.</=
p><p><a href=3D"https://lucykeer.com/notebucket/variable-names-as-sigils-or=
-handles/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" class=3D"underlink bluelink" =
tabindex=3D"-1">Variable names as handles or sigils</a> got a bit of intere=
st at the beginning of the year. I'd like to revisit that topic at some poi=
nt and do a less half-arsed job. I also like <a href=3D"https://lucykeer.co=
m/notebucket/three-pass-writing/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" class=
=3D"underlink bluelink" tabindex=3D"-1">Three pass writing</a>.</p><h2>News=
letter</h2><p>I wrote about a pretty random set of topics this year. As wel=
l as the partimento post I covered <a href=3D"https://bucketoverflow.substa=
ck.com/p/april-2024-what-the-hell-is-a-body" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noope=
ner" class=3D"underlink bluelink" tabindex=3D"-1">Deleuze's "body without o=
rgans"</a>, <a href=3D"https://bucketoverflow.substack.com/p/july-2024-real=
ism-for-realistic-people" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" class=3D"under=
link bluelink" tabindex=3D"-1">Hasok Chang on realism</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://bucketoverflow.substack.com/p/c-s-lewis-on-ai-art" target=3D"_blank" rel=
=3D"noopener" class=3D"underlink bluelink" tabindex=3D"-1">C. S. Lewis's <e=
m>An Experiment in Criticism</em></a>, <a href=3D"https://bucketoverflow.su=
bstack.com/p/notes-on-notation-must-die" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"=
 class=3D"underlink bluelink" tabindex=3D"-1">Tantacrul's YouTube video on =
music notation</a> and <a href=3D"https://bucketoverflow.substack.com/p/jan=
uary-2024-relativity-cooked-three" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" class=
=3D"underlink bluelink" tabindex=3D"-1">special relativity</a>. </p><p>I'm =
not sure it adds up to much but I had fun.</p><h2>Physics</h2><p>I've sligh=
tly lost track of what I did here. At the beginning of the year I was in a =
phase of reading about relativity. Then I think I just dropped physics for =
a few months until the old negative probability obsession returned. In the =
last couple of months I've been trying to finally write up some of my negat=
ive probability stuff properly, which has been slow and frustrating. I'm cu=
rrently procrastinating by reading some quantum foundations papers I've bee=
n meaning to get to for ages.</p><p>I'm struggling a bit with being so isol=
ated from any community of practice. I'm still in the physics society but i=
t's been fairly quiet recently and I don't feel particularly connected to i=
t.</p><h2>Reading</h2><p>Here's what I can remember (I never keep a list bu=
t I like to try and figure it out at the end of the year):</p><ul><li>Alcot=
t =E2=80=93 <em>Little Women</em></li><li>Austen =E2=80=93 <em>Mansfield Pa=
rk</em></li><li>Montgomery =E2=80=93 <em>Anne of Green Gables</em> and many=
 sequels</li><li>Sassoon =E2=80=93 <em>Memoirs of a Fox-hunting Man</em> an=
d <em>Memoirs of an Infantry Officer</em></li><li>Rao =E2=80=93 <em>Tempo</=
em></li><li>Harrison =E2=80=93 <em>Wish I Was Here</em></li><li>Nobes =
=E2=80=93 <em>Illusion or reality? Are we teaching what FM Alexander was te=
aching?</em></li><li>Alexander =E2=80=93 <em>The Use of the Self</em></li><=
li>Jones =E2=80=93 <em>Freedom to Change. </em>Strong recommend for this on=
e if you're going to read an Alexander Technique book.</li><li>Lewis =
=E2=80=93 <em>An Experiment in Criticism</em>, <em>The Great Divorce</em>, =
<em>They Asked for a Paper</em></li></ul><p>Plus some of:</p><ul><li>Gallwe=
y =E2=80=93 <em>The Inner Game of Tennis</em></li><li>McLeod =E2=80=93 <em>=
Wake up to your Life</em></li><li>Gjerdingen =E2=80=93 <em>Music in the Gal=
ant Style. </em>"Some of" is a bit of an understatement, because I've spent=
 a ton of time at the piano playing through the excerpts, but I haven't tri=
ed to read through the whole thing. Instead I work through a new pattern wh=
en I start to appreciate it.</li><li>Mortensen =E2=80=93 <em>The Pianist=
=E2=80=99s Guide to Historic Improvisation</em></li><li>Chang =E2=80=93 <em=
>Realism for Realistic People</em></li><li>Alexander =E2=80=93 <em>Construc=
tive Conscious Control of the Individual</em></li><li>White =E2=80=93 <em>T=
he Once and Future King</em></li></ul><p>No particular themes, except you c=
an see the influence of my two new interests. </p><h2>Other stuff</h2><p>I =
already talked about partimento practice and Alexander Technique. The other=
 feature of 2024 was trying to adapt to the weird state of the internet. I =
lost patience with Twitter but haven=E2=80=99t yet found a home anywhere el=
se. Hanging around on discord is nice but I miss the open internet.</p><p>N=
ear the end of the year I decided to reduce the amount of time I spend read=
ing stuff on the internet, as it wasn't like I was having much fun there an=
yway. I tried a drastic <a href=3D"https://lucykeer.com/notebucket/a-week-o=
f-minimal-internet/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" class=3D"underlink =
